<div class="columns">
  <section class="column-main dark padded about">
    <h1 class="page-heading">Debates in the Digital Humanities</h1>


    <h3 class="section-heading">About the Series</h3>
    <p><%= link_to({ controller: 'debates', action: 'index', edition_id: 2 }) do %><span class="italicized">Debates in the Digital Humanities 2016</span><% end %>
    marks the start of a new book series from the University of Minnesota Press. Building on <%= link_to({ controller: 'debates', action: 'index', edition_id: 2 }) do %>the first edition of <span class="italicized">Debates in the Digital Humanities</span><% end %>, the series will explore the most compelling debates in the field as they emerge. As digital humanities scholars and practitioners, along with their critics, continue to articulate the field, Debates in the Digital Humanities will track the issues and tensions at stake in their discussions of methods, practices, theories, controversies, projects, and politics.</p>
    <br>
    <p>To read more about the series, <%= link_to({ controller: 'debates', action: 'index', text_id: @aboutText }) do %>click here<% end %>.</p>
    
    <%= render "shared/book_blurbs" %>

    <h3 class="section-heading">About the Platform</h3>
    <p>The <span class="italicized">Debates in the Digital Humanities</span> platform was launched in 2013 in conjunction with the open-access edition of the first <span class="italicized">Debates in the Digital Humanities</span> volume. Since then, the platform has expanded to include features that allow readers to interact with the material by marking passages, and adding terms to a crowdsourced index; the platform also includes atom feeds and APIs.</p>
    <br>
    <p>In 2016, the platform was redesigned to include the content associated with Debates in the Digital Humanities 2016. For the latest updates, see the <a href="/news">news page</a>.</p>

